@DanielDylanWray Some people's priorities change as they get older/ have families and jobs. Music used to be a main definer of your tribe/ identity now the internet seemingly dominates for younger gens. I still love music in my forties but I agree that communal enjoyment isn't what it was. 4/4

@DanielDylanWray The majors have focussed on a handful of names to dominate the streaming market. But these artists are largely santized so many older fans think new music "isn't for them" because they aren't as exposed to new/independent music which is where the cutting edge is. 3/4

@DanielDylanWray The algorithm spits up discovery now, listening has become more fragmented into personal or "genre" categories on radio/playlists. You don't have cultural bundles with a significant audience like TOTPs/Peel had where you you might find an artist you might not have sought out.2/3

@DanielDylanWray Interesting piece. I think there are a lot of factors as you say nostalgia is a big factor as are the choices with leisure time now. Streaming and the Internet has shifted our relationship and the value of music. This is linked to the #BrokenRecord campaign. 1/2
